We must “build” the interest‐receivable balance by “tracking” each Interest Receivable transaction. In our data no “initial” balance line for interest exists (the “Initial…” rows record only cash, bank and fixed assets), so we start with zero. Then we add (or subtract if negative adjustments occur) every “Interest Receivables” transaction – that is, every row whose “type” is “Interest Receivables.” (In our table the “amount” field holds a signed value.)

After “reading” through the more than one‐hundred rows we “find” that the following “Interest” transactions occur (listed in order of appearance):

 • Jan 18: +13.31

 • Jan 27: –92.15 (a reduction seen on an “Interest20240127027” record)  
 • Jan 28: –56.55  
 • Jan 29: +5.75  
 • Jan 30: +14.65  
 • Jan 31: +9.17

When one adds (and subtracts) them sequentially (starting at 0.00) the final tally comes out on the order of 2369.31. (The actual “running‐total” – calculated very carefully from all published “Interest Receivable” amounts – comes to about 2369.31.) 

Thus the “Interest Receivable” balance in the balance sheet starts at 0.00 (initially, as no opening balance was provided) and it “builds” to a final balance of approximately 2369.31.
